ial:BookSources/1-60506-119-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/1-60506-119-0\">1-60506-119-0</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Indian+Fairy+Tales&amp;rft.pages=69-73&amp;rft.edition=1913&amp;rft.pub=Forgotten+Books&amp;rft.date=1892&amp;rft.isbn=1-60506-119-0&amp;rft.aulast=Jacobs&amp;rft.aufirst=Joseph&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Tiger%2C+the+Brahmin+and+the+Jackal\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> where it appears as The Tiger, the Brahman, and the Jackal. Jacobs gives his source as \"Steel-Temple, Wideawake Stories, pp. 116-20; first published in Indian Antiquary, xii. p. 170 seq.\"\nIt can be found online <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=vhHkp2r0GEAC&amp;printsec=frontcover#PPR9,M1\">here</a> at Google Books and <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.heritage-history.com/www/heritage.php?Dir=books&amp;MenuItem=display&amp;author=jacobs&amp;book=indian&amp;story=tiger\">here</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20110711163649/http://www.heritage-history.com/www/heritage.php?Dir=books&amp;MenuItem=display&amp;author=jacobs&amp;book=indian&amp;story=tiger\">Archived</a> 2011-07-11 at the <a href=\"/wiki/Wayback_Machine\" title=\"Wayback Machine\">Wayback Machine</a>. with its illustration.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Jacobs in his <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.authorama.com/indian-fairy-tales-31.html\">notes</a> on the tale mentions that \"No less than 94 parallels are given by Prof. K. Krohn in his elaborate discussion of this fable in his dissertation, Mann und Fuchs, (Helsingfors, 1891), pp. 38-60\"</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"